-- Spanish Stocks: ACS, Bankinter, Pastor, Santander, Telecinco
-- Alexis Xydias
-- 2010-07-12T16:07:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-12/spanish-stocks-acs-bankinter-pastor-santander-telecinco-are-active.html

          
          
             Spain’s  IBEX 35 Index (IBEX)  lost 69.1, or
0.7 percent, to 10.058.2, ending a six-day rally.  
 The following were among the most active stocks in the
Spanish market today.  
 Actividades de Construccion & Servicios SA  (ACS SM) dropped
25 cents, or 0.8 percent, to 31.96 euros. Spain won’t award
contracts for new public-works projects until 2016, El Mundo
reported, citing unidentified people who attended a meeting with
Deputy Minister for Infrastructure Victor Morlan.  
 ArcelorMittal (MT)  , the Luxembourg-based steelmaker,
fell 40 cents, or 1.7 percent, to 23.31 euros. The spot price of
 iron ore  delivered to China, the world’s biggest buyer of the
steelmaking ingredient, slumped to its lowest level this year as
steel production in the Asian nation slows.  
 Bankinter SA (BKT)   retreated 11 cents, or 1.9 percent,
to 5.50 euros. Banco Pastor SA (PAS SM) fell 4 cents, or 1
percent, to 4.07 euros.  Banco Espanol de Credito SA  (BTO SM)
rose 1 cent, or 0.1 percent, to 7.50 euros. The three mid-sized
banks may need to raise 1.16 billion euros ($1.47 billion) in
capital to cope with potential losses under a “stressed”
scenario, El Economista reported, citing estimates by JPMorgan
Chase & Co.  
 Banco Santander SA (SAN)   dropped 8.3 cents, or 0.8
percent, to 9.89 euros. Spain’s largest bank agreed to buy 173
German retail bank branches from SEB AB for about 555 million
euros ($698 million) to expand in Europe’s largest economy.  
 Separately, Santander aims to increase its 10 percent
market share in  Latin America  by two or three percentage points,
Latin American head  Francisco Luzon  told Expansion in an
interview.  
      Gestevision Telecinco SA (TL5)  (TL5 SM) advanced 16 cents, or 1.9
percent, to 8.37 euros. The holder of the Spanish rights for the
main games of soccer’s World Cup advanced after Spain beat the
Netherlands to win the tournament for the first time in its 80-
year history.  
 Iberdrola SA (IBE)   declined 2.4 cents, or 0.5 percent,
to 5.13 euros, the first loss in eight days. A court rejected a
request by Actividades de Construccion & Servicios to suspend a
decision by Iberdrola shareholders that blocked the builder from
the power company’s board, Cinco Dias reported.  
